    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-09-23T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-09-23T05:00:00-05:00" n="492"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d492">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">674.84A/9–2352: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 492<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Egypt (<persName corresp="#p_CJ1"
                            type="from">Caffery</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d492fn1">Repeated to Tel Aviv.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-09-23T12:00:00+02:00"
                            >September 23, 1952—noon.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>763. We have queried Aly <persName corresp="#p_MMA1">Maher</persName>’s Chief of
                    Cabinet in <gloss target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss> who in fact drafted note
                    which formed first encl Emb despatch 405 Sept 8. He says that Aly <persName
                        corresp="#p_MMA1">Maher</persName> had in mind “all” <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                        >UN</gloss> resolutions on Pal to which Israelis had not given compliance.
                    Obviously Egypt Govt is most interested in resolutions re internationalization
                    of Jerusalem and Arab refugees with particular emphasis on return to homes of
                    latter. When Chief of Cabinet went on to say that by “all” Aly <persName
                        corresp="#p_MMA1">Maher</persName> also meant original <gloss
                        target="#t_UNGA1">UNGA</gloss> res on partition of Pal, we pointed out that
                    this seemed odd since Egypt and other Arab Govts were on record as fundamentally
                    opposing that res.</p>
                <p>Our estimate is that Aly <persName corresp="#p_MMA1">Maher</persName>’s ltr was
                    not drafted with any great precision of thought. As our recent tels have
                    indicated Egypt official interest has been so concentrated on domestic reform
                    that peace with Israel has not occupied a primary place. However, we discerning
                    trends both in official and in potentially official opinion to face up to fact
                    that Egypt’s interest will best be served by coming to peace settlement with
                    Israel. Army offs in very tentative way have talked with us, and even with Brit,
                    on mil advantages of calling off Israeli “war” and <gloss target="#t_FonOff1"
                        >FonOff</gloss> off cited above yestd said that eventually peace might be
                    reached on line of present boundaries. Perhaps more significant was indication
                    to me Sept 19 by former <gloss target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss>
                    <persName corresp="#p_AMG1">Sirry</persName> that “if he were made <gloss
                        target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss> again” he wld be able to arrange peace
                    with Israel. We also note as reported <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss>
                    760 Sept 22, rptd Tel Aviv 12,<note n="2" xml:id="d492fn2">Not printed.</note>
                    that Aly <persName corresp="#p_MMA1">Maher</persName> led opposition in Arab <pb
                        facs="1048" n="1008" xml:id="pg_1008"/> league to Jamali’s proposal that
                    Jews in Arab countries be treated like Arabs in Israel. However, for immed
                    future we feel that emphasis on internal affairs and on arrangement of
                    differences with Brit still relegates Israel peace issue to background. <gloss
                        target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss> source above states no further overtures
                    from Israeli side similar to those described in encls one and two ref despatch
                    have been recd.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
